            {
                "s2_paper_id": "4fe263127c5dae2717f3dc6a387efa295bd4c720",
                "title": "The Icla/Chullpamoko excavation and final remarks",
                "year": 2021,
                "venue": "Nawpa Pacha",
                "citation_count": 0,
                "reference_count": 73,
                "abstract": "Here we present an English translation of the last chapter of the book Beitr\u00e4ge zur Arch\u00e4ologie Boliviens (Walter 1966), which describes the results of a major German expedition. In addition to this chapter, the book describes the expedition\u2019s excavations in Oruro, at the site Huancarani, and in Cochabamba, the sites Cliza-Chullpapata and Mizque-Lakatambo. In the introduction, Hermann Trimborn explains that one of the project\u2019s goals was to reveal that Bolivia\u2019s rich cultural diversity went beyond the Lake Titicaca Basin. The 1958 expedition had the support of the University Museum of Cochabamba, at the time headed by Dick E. Ibarra Grasso. It was led by Hans Dietrich Disselhoff and organized by Berlin\u2019s Museum f\u00fcr V\u00f6lkerkunde. Disselhoff described Walter as an ethnologist and prehistorian, a man of few words, self-disciplined, and responsible. He was the only one on the team not afraid of heights so he was able to reach the sites Inca Machay and Pucara de Oroncota. He reportedly mapped Pucara de Oroncota and did all the drawings of the excavations and artifacts. This volume is a classic for German-speaking archaeologists working in Bolivia, but is not widely known in the US or Latin America, in part because German is not a working language of most Andean archaeologists. It was issued as a supplementary volume of the journal Baessler-Archiv, which was first published in 1911 and is available at https:// digi.evifa.de/. Walter\u2019s supplementary volume, however, is not yet available online and can be difficult to locate, even in university libraries. Furthermore, connections to better-known sites",
                "authors": [
